#week-title("Two", "Lead, Saturn, and the First Matter")

=== Core Teaching

Lead holds a unique position in the alchemical tradition: it is simultaneously
the least perfect of the seven metals and the starting point from which all the
others are understood to derive. The tradition calls lead the *prima materia* of
the metallic kingdom in its most accessible form — the metal in its most
contracted, most heavy, most Saturnine expression, but therefore also the metal
that has the furthest to travel and the greatest potential transformation ahead
of it.

*Saturn's qualities in the mineral kingdom.* Lead is cold, heavy, soft, and
slow to react. It absorbs other metals in fusion (as antimony absorbs and
purifies gold). Its oxide (litharge) forms quickly in air — lead "breathes" its
oxidation products more readily than any other metal. In this respect it is
paradoxically both the most fixed (the heaviest, most contracted) and the most
open to oxidation (the most subject to the corroding power of the atmosphere).

*The alchemical symbol of Saturn.* The symbol ♄ (a cross above a crescent,
or a scythe) encodes the principle: the cross of the four elements fixed and
condensed beneath the crescent of the lunar-astral influence. Time and
restriction are Saturn's domains — he is the great limiter, the boundary-setter,
the force that brings all things to their crystallised conclusion.

*Why lead comes first in mineral study.* Working with lead before any other
metal grounds the practitioner's perception in the most accessible and most
revealing of the metallic forces. Lead has no pretension. It is exactly what
it appears to be: heavy, dull, patient, persistent. The practitioner who has
genuinely meditated with lead for twenty minutes knows something about the
Saturn principle that no amount of reading can provide.

*Safety note.* Lead is toxic. Handle all lead with nitrile gloves. Wash hands
after any contact. Do not heat lead indoors or without adequate ventilation —
lead fumes are a serious health hazard. For Year Two purposes, handling cold
lead for meditative purposes (with gloves) is the extent of the practical work.
Heated lead work belongs to Year Three under proper conditions.

